%%TITLE
Bacteremic pneumococcal pneumonia: clinical outcomes and preliminary results of inflammatory response.
%%ABSTRACT
Further examination of clinical outcomes and inflammatory response of bacteremic pneumococcal community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) is of great interest to enhance the care of patients with pneumococcal CAP.This is a secondary analysis of the Community Acquired Pneumonia Organization (CAPO) to compare the time to clinical stability (TCS), length of hospital stay (LOS), and in-hospital mortality of hospitalized pneumococcal CAP patients with and without bacteremia. To measure the effect of bacteremia in pneumococcal CAP patients on outcomes, we modeled all-cause in-hospital mortality using a Poisson regression model, and TCS and LOS using Cox proportional hazards models. Adjusted multivariate regression models were also used to predict the probability of occurrence of each of the study outcomes. To investigate the inflammatory response, we measured the plasma levels of pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines [tumor necrosis factor (TNF)-Î±, interleukin (IL)-1rÎ±, IL-6, IL-8, IL-10], inflammatory biomarkers [C-reactive protein (CRP), pro-calcitonin (PCT), and B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP)], and peripheral blood neutrophil responses in 10 patients, 4 bacteremic and 6 non-bacteremic pneumococcal CAP, upon admission and every other day during the first 6 days of hospitalization. Functional data were presented as median and standard error of the median (SEM); due to small number of samples no statistical comparisons were performed between groups.From 833 pneumococcal CAP patients, 394 patients (47 %) were bacteremic. Bacteremic pneumococcal CAP were less likely to reach TCS with an adjusted hazard ratio (AHR) of 0.82 (95 % CI 0.69-0.97; p = 0.02) and had higher in-hospital mortality with an AHR of 1.63 (95 % CI 1.06-2.50, p = 0.026). Bacteremic pneumococcal CAP patients had a longer LOS than non-bacteremic pneumococcal CAP (p < 0.003). Higher plasma levels of CRP, PCT, and BNP were found in bacteremic than in non-bacteremic patients. The bacteremic group had consistently higher plasma levels of both pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines. The blood neutrophil functional responses were similar in both groups of patients.Bacteremic pneumococcal CAP patients were significantly associated with higher in-hospital mortality, lower TCS, and longer LOS. HIV-infected patients showed a greater mortality which was not statistically significant. Bacteremic pneumococcal CAP patients had higher levels of biomarkers and systemic cytokines.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Study design and population
This study was a combination of two study databases. The clinical outcomes of hospitalized patients with pneumococ- cal CAP were evaluated by performing a secondary analy- sis of the CAPO international cohort study database. CAPO has been described previously [] and the case report form as well as other details of this study may be reviewed at . Local Institutional Review Board permission was requested at each participating institution, and consent was waived. Inflammatory responses of hos- pitalized patients with pneumococcal CAP were evaluated using a secondary analysis of a prospective cohort study. The University of Louisville Human Subjects Protection Program office approved this study with consent from the participating individuals (IRB #07.0182, #0009, at UofL and Robley Rex VA, Louisville, KY, respectively). This was a prospective study by members of the Community- Acquired Pneumonia Inflammatory Study Group (CAP- ISG) at the University of Louisville Hospital and the Rob- ley Rex Veterans Affairs Medical Center in Louisville, KY from February 14, 2011 to April 14, 2012. IRB approval was obtained from both institutions.
Inclusion criteria
Inclusion criteria for this study included (1) diagnosis of CAP, defined as the presence of a new pulmonary infil- trate on chest radiograph at the time of hospitalization, plus either a new or increased cough with or without spu- tum production, or an abnormal temperature (<35.6 or
>37.8 °C), or an abnormal serum leukocyte count (i.e., leukocytosis, left shift, or leukopenia) as defined by local laboratory values []; (2) S. pneumoniae identified by a positive culture of a respiratory sample, blood, or pleural fluid or a positive urinary antigen.
Exclusion criteria
Patients with CAP were excluded if blood cultures were not obtained at the time of hospitalization.
Study groups
Patients with positive blood cultures for S. pneumoniae were classified as Group 1 (bacteremic pneumococ- cal CAP). Patients with negative blood cultures for S.
pneumoniae were classified as Group 2 (non-bacteremic pneumococcal CAP).
Study variables
The variables considered in each study participant were grouped as follows: (1) demographics (age, sex, and nurs- ing home residency); (2) comorbid conditions/history [can- cer, congestive heart failure (CHF), chronic obstructive pul- monary disease (COPD), human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection, diabetes mellitus, diabetes mellitus with glycemia of 250 mg/dL, liver disease, renal disease, cer- ebrovascular accident, and alcohol and/or illegal drug use];
(3) physical examinations (temperature, heart rate, systolic blood pressure, and respiratory rate); (4) laboratory tests [arterial pH, sodium, hematocrit, partial pressure of oxygen in arterial blood (PaO2), pleural effusion, blood urea nitro- gen (BUN), multilobar infiltrate]; (5) severity of CAP [ICU admission, pneumonia severity index (PSI) []—high severity of disease included patients with a PSI risk class of IV or V, and altered mental status, which was defined as a new presentation of confusion, delirium, obtundation, stu- por, or coma]; and (6) world region study samples recruited (United States/Canada, Europe, and Latin America).
Study outcomes
Time to clinical stability (TCS)
The following American Thoracic Society criteria [], which define a patient as clinically stable and ready to be switched to therapy with oral antibiotics (so-called switch therapy), were followed: (1) improved cough and shortness of breath; (2) lack of fever for at least 8 h; (3) improving leu- kocytosis (decreased at least 10 % from the previous day); and (4) tolerating oral intake with adequate gastrointestinal absorption. Patients were evaluated daily during the first 7 days of hospitalization to determine the day when clinical stability was reached. A patient was defined as clinically sta- ble when these four criteria were met on a single day.
Length of hospital stay (LOS)
LOS was defined in days and was calculated for each patient as the day of hospital discharge minus the day of hospital admission. Patients hospitalized for >14 days and patients who died prior to 14 days were censored at 14 days.
All‑cause in‑hospital mortality
All-cause in-hospital mortality was defined as the sum of all patients with a final clinical outcome classified as
“dead.” The final clinical outcome “dead or alive” was eval- uated at the time of hospital discharge. The final clinical outcome for patients who were still hospitalized at day 28 was considered as “alive.”
Inflammatory cytokines and neutrophil functional studies
We have also conducted a subgroup analysis of plasma lev- els of inflammatory markers, plasma pro- and anti-inflam- matory cytokine levels, and peripheral blood neutrophil responses to stimuli in a small subgroup of patients with bacteremic (n 4) and non-bacteremic (n 6) pneumo- coccal CAP during hospitalization. Please see the supple- mental appendix for a detailed description of study subjects and laboratory methods.
Statistical analysis
Baseline patient characteristics between hospitalized patients with bacteremic pneumococcal CAP and non- bacteremic pneumococcal CAP were compared using Chi-squared or Fisher’s exact tests for categorical vari- ables and the Mann–Whitney U test for continuous vari- ables. Kaplan–Meier survival curves were used to compare the LOS and TCS between the same two groups. Similar curves were created for LOS, stratified by patients admitted to the ICU vs. those admitted to the ward.
To evaluate the adjusted effect of bacteremic pneumo- coccal CAP vs. non-bacteremic pneumococcal CAP on all-cause in-hospital mortality, a Poisson regression model with robust error variance was used []. The model was adjusted for pneumonia severity index (PSI), history of pneumococcal vaccine, and ICU admission status. To account for non-linear associations between the PSI and in-hospital-mortality, the index was modeled with a 4-knot restricted cubic spline function. This model was repeated for patients admitted to the ICU as well as those admitted to the ward, omitting ICU admission status as a covariate.
Cox proportional hazards regression models were used to evaluate the adjusted impact of bacteremia on LOS and TCS. The LOS was modeled for patients admitted to the ICU and those admitted to the ward separately, with each model adjusting for the splined PSI as above, and history of pneumococcal vaccine. The time to clinical stability model was adjusted for the splined PSI as above, history of pneu- mococcal vaccine, and ICU admission status.
Functional data were presented as descriptive parameters using median and standard error of the median (SEM), but due to small number of samples, no statistical comparisons of the functional data between groups were performed. GraphPad Prism 5.0 (GraphPad Software, La Jolla, CA) and R version 2.15 () were used to
generate graphs for functional data and cytokine and neu- trophil data are presented as medians and standard errors.
